            },
            "answer_text": "No. Some people (including me) often use the term Persian interchangeably with Iranian. But, really, Persians are a subset of Iranians defined by culture, region, and genetics while Iranian includes a number of groups, Medes, Kurds, etc. not considered Persian. In Iran, the data is sketchy. Clearly the vast majority are Muslim and Shi\u2019ih Muslim. A significant minority is Sunni (or also Sufi) Muslim. In terms of other beliefs: Atheist and agnostic are most probably (by far) the largest and fastest growing non-Muslim beliefs (some suppressed or not openly declared in Iran, but many Persians/Iranians in the \u201cWest\u201d that have emigrated either openly or privately are no longer Muslims)Baha\u2019is are next largest. There are maybe 300,000+ remaining in Iran but once there may have been as many as 600,000+ in Iran before 1979. Many Baha\u2019is left Iran. Baha\u2019is were encouraged and warned to leave or at least move assets out prior to 1979. Over time before the Revolution some emigrated out of Iran, and many additionally have left over time (especially in the 1980s) such that there are many additional \u201cPersian\u201d Baha\u2019is outside of Iran (many now married to persons of other nationalities or second or even third generations since emigrating). Baha\u2019is are most heavily persecuted in Iran. See Persecution of Bah\u00e1'\u00eds - Wikipedia and the listed links to UN and international NGO reports.Christians (such as Armenian Orthodox in the Northwestern region and others) are probably next largest after Baha\u2019is but have been declining in numbers as well due to departures.A very small remnant of the Jewish community remains in Iran (most have now emigrated and some families had converted to the Baha\u2019i Faith beginning in the 1880s and progressively over time).A small remnant of Zoroastrians remain in Iran (large percentage converted to the Baha\u2019i Faith in the late 1800s and over time and others have emigrated, some to join Parsi communities in India and others left to \u201cWestern\u201d countries).There are small numbers of other religions such as Hindus, Buddhists, Yazidis, and Babi\u2019s also exist in Iran. (The Bab declared a religion in 1844 and had a significant following quickly develop but many were killed or persecuted and most of the remainder became Baha\u2019is. Maybe a thousand Babi\u2019s remain that did not become Baha\u2019is today, and many may not be identified publicly as Babi\u2019s.)",
