                "name": "Orem Frien",
                "href": "/profile/Orem-Frien"
            },
            "answer_text": "MOST BUT NOT ALL. Most Persians are Shiite Muslims, but there are significant religious minorities among Persians. The largest minority of Persians are Sunni Muslims, especially those outside of Iran, such as the Persians in Afghanistan, Tajikistan, and Uzbekistan. After the Muslims, the largest minority would have to be Atheists and Agnostics. While accurate numbers cannot be recorded since conversion out of Islam is illegal in Iran, there are certainly millions of Atheist Persians. Other Persian religious minorities include: Christians, both recent converts and long-time members of the Church. The most common forms of Christianity are Oriental Orthodoxy (Church of the East, Nestorianism, Armenian) and modern Protestantism (Evangelical and Episcopalian/Anglican)Zoroastrians, the historic religion of Persia, the largest number of Persian Zoroastrians is near the Fire Temples at Yazd (and in Teheran). There is another related religion of Mandaeanism.Jews, there are Persian Jews throughout the world, but primarily in the United States and IsraelBaha\u2019i, there are at least a few hundred Persian Baha\u2019i. There are also a few dozen thousand Azalis and Babis (which are related religions to Baha\u2019i)Yazadi and Ahl-e-Haqq, these are indigenous Kurdish faiths that some Persians practiceNote on Persian vs. Iranian Most people have been trying to correct you to use the term \u201cIranian\u201d instead of \u201cPersian\u201d. This may be incorrect. \u201cIranian\u201d is a national term. It refers to the country of Iran and its citizens. \u201cPersian\u201d is an ethnic term. It refers to the people who speak Farsi as a native language and engage in Persian culture. 61\u201365% of Iranians are Persians. Roughly half of Persians are Iranians (since Persian includes Tajiks in both Afghanistan and Tajikistan and ethnic Persians outside of the Middle East.) ",
