            "answer_text": "On paper, most Iranians are Shi\u2019a Muslims, but the reality is more complicated. First, you're not allowed to convert to a religion other than Islam and there are strong insentives to dissuade you from claiming atheism openly as your personal preference. There are two major groups in Iran. One is the religious type who firmly identify with Shi'a Islam and views Iran as the world defender of this creed. The other group is what many call nationalists. Nationalists like to trace their heritage all the way back to the time of Cyrus the Great. Most nationalists I've met claim to be atheists. Many Iranians of all generations seem to be disillusioned by state sponsored religion to a certain extent. I think this is turning a lot of people away from their faith, even if you won't see it in any official study. And of course there are Jews, Christians and Zoroastrians who have a special immunity from a certain number of Islamic restrictions as long as they don't try to convert other people. There\u2019s also Baha'is , but don't tell anyone. ;-) ",
